---
description: Enforce spec-driven development — no implementation without a spec
alwaysApply: false
globs: ["specs/**", "src/**", "frontend/**"]
---

## What This Rule Does

Ensures that every feature follows a mandatory, sequential pipeline before a
single line of production code is written. The spec is the source of truth —
not the code, not the commit message, not the PR description. If a spec does
not exist, implementation cannot begin. If the spec changes after implementation
starts, a new clarification cycle is required.

---

## The Pipeline (Mandatory and Sequential)

```
analyze → clarify → constitution → plan → specify → implement → checklist → commit
```

Each stage gates the next. Skipping any stage or running them out of order is
a rule violation. The agent must refuse to run a later-stage skill if earlier
stages have not produced their output artifacts.

---

## Gate Rules

| Gate | Condition |
|------|-----------|
| `speckit-implement` | Requires `specs/features/[feature-slug].md` to exist |
| `speckit-git-commit` | Requires `speckit-checklist` to have passed in this session |
| `speckit-checklist` | Requires all TASK items for the feature marked Done in progress.md |
| `speckit-specify` | Requires `specs/plans/[feature-slug]-plan.md` to exist |
| `speckit-plan` | Requires `specs/constitutions/[feature-slug]-constitution.md` to exist |
| `speckit-constitution` | Requires `specs/clarifications/[feature-slug].md` to exist |
| `speckit-clarify` | Requires analysis from `speckit-analyze` (inline or in a file) |

**Never skip `speckit-clarify`.** Question count and format are governed by
`.cursor/rules/05-planning-rigor.mdc` — never fewer than 5 questions, scaled
by complexity, and every question must be presented as labeled options, not
open blanks.

---

## Spec Immutability After Implementation Starts

Specs are **append-only** once `/speckit-implement` has been run for any task
in the feature.

- **Allowed:** Adding an `## Addendum` section with new information
- **Allowed:** Correcting a factual error (wrong field name, wrong HTTP method) with a dated note
- **Forbidden:** Editing acceptance criteria to match incomplete code
- **Forbidden:** Removing out-of-scope items after they were built

Scope changes require:
1. A new `/speckit-clarify` cycle tagged as `[Scope Change - feature-slug-v2]`
2. A new spec file `specs/features/[feature-slug]-v2.md`
3. New task entries in `memory-bank/progress.md`
4. A note in the original spec pointing to the v2 spec

---

## Spec File Naming

```
specs/features/[kebab-case-feature-name].md
specs/clarifications/[kebab-case-feature-name].md
specs/constitutions/[kebab-case-feature-name]-constitution.md
specs/plans/[kebab-case-feature-name]-plan.md
specs/retros/[kebab-case-feature-name]-retro.md
```

Feature names must be **kebab-case**, descriptive, and unique within the
project. Avoid vague names like `fix-bug` or `update-api` — use
`add-payment-retry-logic` or `user-profile-avatar-upload` instead.

---

## Spec Traceability

Every commit message must reference the spec filename:
```
feat(application): add payment retry handler

Spec: specs/features/add-payment-retry-logic.md
Closes #42
```

Every test that validates an acceptance criterion must have a comment
identifying which criterion it covers:
```csharp
// AC-3: Retry must not exceed 3 attempts for network errors
[Fact]
public async Task Handle_NetworkError_RetriesMaxThreeTimes() { ... }
```

---

## Full-Stack Features

A full-stack feature has **one spec** that covers both the API contract and
the UI behavior. Never split a single user-facing feature into separate
backend and frontend specs — they belong together so contract alignment is
visible in one document.

---

## Violations

### ❌ Violation 1 — Implementing without a spec

**Trigger:** User asks: *"Just add an export-to-CSV button on the reports page."*

**Bad behavior:**
> Agent immediately generates a `CsvExportButton.tsx` component and a
> `/api/reports/export` endpoint with no spec, no acceptance criteria, and
> no test plan.

**Correct behavior:**
> Agent responds: *"Before generating code I need a spec. Let me run
> `/speckit-analyze` first — it will take 2 minutes and means we won't
> need to rewrite the component when edge cases come up in review."*
> Agent runs `/speckit-analyze` → `/speckit-clarify` before touching any
> source file.

---

### ❌ Violation 2 — Editing a spec to match incomplete code

**Trigger:** During implementation, the handler turns out to be more complex
than expected. User says: *"Just remove AC-4 from the spec, we'll do it next sprint."*

**Bad behavior:**
> Agent deletes AC-4 from `specs/features/payment-retry.md` so the checklist passes.

**Correct behavior:**
> Agent responds: *"The spec is append-only after implementation starts. I'll
> add a dated note to `specs/features/payment-retry.md` under an `## Addendum`
> section documenting that AC-4 is deferred to the next sprint, and create a
> GitHub issue for it so it's tracked. The original criterion stays in the spec."*
